As to the orthography of the word in the text, we find it vari- ously written soracum, saracum, sarracam, and serv-acum. Soractem is met with in Plautus, but with the penult. short ; therefore they seem to be different words.—Sarraczcm, a kind of common cart, or waggon, which was used by the country people of Italy, for conveying the produce of their fields, trees, aud the like—Its name, as well as the fact that it was used by several barbarous natium, show that it was introduced from them into Italy. Capitolinus (Anton. Philosoph. 13.) states that during a plague at Rome the mortality was so great, that it was found necessary to carry the dead bodies out of the city upon sar- raca. Several barbarous nations used these waggons also in war, and placed them around their camps as a fortification. Juvenal has satiri- cally used the word to denote the constellation usually called the Plau- strum, ‘⁴ Charles’ Wain,'’ in Sat. v. 22.
